\end{document} Explained more intuitively, SAR formulations attempt to relate the given compound descriptors to experimentally-determined bioactivity markers. While earlier models for ‘quantitative SAR’ (QSAR) involved simple linear formulations for fitting properties and various statistical techniques (e.g., multivariate regression, principal component analysis), nonlinear optimization techniques combined with other visual and computational techniques are more common today [448]. The problem remains very challenging, with rigorous frameworks continuously being sought.

To compare compounds in the database to each other and to new targets, a quantitative assessment can be based on common structural features. Whether characterized by topological (chemical-formula based) or 3D features, this assessment can be broadly based on the vectorial chemical descriptors provided by various computer packages. A target function f is defined, typically based on the Euclidean distance function between vector pairs, δ, where 15.3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
